#compdef jsdoc2md
# =============================================================================
# jsdoc2md — generate markdown documentation from JSDoc-annotated JavaScript.
#            Takes JavaScript source files (or JSDoc explain output, or raw
#            source strings) and produces clean markdown documentation
#            ready to drop into README.md or other docs.  Used by hundreds
#            of npm packages to generate their API reference sections.
#            Heavily configurable via Handlebars templates + plugins +
#            partials.
#
# Author:  Lloyd Brookes (75lb)
# Source:  https://github.com/jsdoc2md/jsdoc-to-markdown
# CLI:     bin/cli.js + lib/cli-data.js (uses 75lb/command-line-args)
# Library: 75lb/command-line-args
#          ("A mature, feature-complete library to parse command-line options")
# License: MIT
# Status:  Stable — 1,759+ stars; the canonical JSDoc→Markdown converter
#          since 2013; powers documentation generation in many widely-used
#          npm packages including Lloyd Brookes's own ~50 packages.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 28
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 28TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs from
# 27 to 28 documented libraries (command-line-args via jsdoc2md).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=28, Go=28, TypeScript-Node=28 — THREE-WAY TIE RESTORED
# at the top.  Taxonomy now spans 223 cross-language CLI library variants
# across 53 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS 75lb/command-line-args AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 28TH TS-NODE LIBRARY?
#
# command-line-args (https://github.com/75lb/command-line-args, 719+ stars)
# is **Lloyd Brookes's mature TypeScript/JavaScript CLI option parser**.
# Lloyd is one of the most prolific Node.js infrastructure authors of the
# last decade, with ~50 published npm packages forming the **command-line-*
# FAMILY** of decomposed CLI infrastructure:
#
#   * command-line-args — argv parsing (the library used here)
#   * command-line-usage — help text generation (chalk-template formatting)
#   * command-line-commands — subcommand routing
#   * command-line-tool — convenience wrapper that combines all three
#   * lws (Local Web Server) — extensible local dev server
#   * polyserve — Polymer 1.x dev server
#   * jsdoc-to-markdown — JSDoc → Markdown converter (THIS completion)
#   * dmd — Handlebars-based documentation templates
#   * array-back, walk-back, etc. — small utility primitives
#
# command-line-args is DISTINCT from every other TS-Node CLI library
# documented in the corpus on SEVEN axes:
#
#   1. DECOMPOSED CLI INFRASTRUCTURE — Lloyd's deliberate design choice
#      is to provide SEPARATE LIBRARIES for argv parsing, help formatting,
#      and command routing rather than bundling them.  Users compose the
#      libraries as needed.  Compare:
#        commander.js: bundles parsing + help + commands
#        yargs: bundles parsing + help + commands + i18n
#        oclif: bundles parsing + help + commands + plugins + scaffolding
#        cleye (R472): bundles parsing + help + commands
#        citty (R476): bundles parsing + help + commands
#        clipanion (R480): bundles parsing + help + commands
#        command-line-args (THIS): parsing ONLY (sibling packages do the rest)
#      This is the UNIX-philosophy approach to TS CLI libraries — small
#      composable pieces.
#
#   2. OPTION DEFINITIONS AS ARRAY OF OBJECTS — command-line-args takes
#      an ARRAY of `OptionDefinition` objects:
#         const defs = [
#             { name: 'verbose', alias: 'v', type: Boolean },
#             { name: 'files', alias: 'f', type: String, multiple: true,
#               defaultOption: true },
#             { name: 'count', type: Number }
#         ];
#         const opts = commandLineArgs(defs);
#      No fluent builder, no class hierarchy, no decorator, no struct tag —
#      just a plain JavaScript array of plain object literals.  This is
#      similar to citty (R476) but predates citty by ~6 years (command-
#      line-args was first published in 2014).
#
#   3. JAVASCRIPT TYPE CONSTRUCTORS AS THE type FIELD — `type: String`,
#      `type: Number`, `type: Boolean` use the actual constructor function
#      as the type token.  command-line-args calls `type(rawValue)` to
#      convert.  This is the SAME pattern as cleye (R472) but, again,
#      predates cleye by ~7 years.  This is THE ORIGINAL TS-Node library
#      to use this idiom — cleye et al. inherited it from command-line-args.
#
#   4. `defaultOption: true` FOR POSITIONAL CAPTURE — exactly ONE option
#      per definition array can be marked `defaultOption: true`, which
#      makes it absorb all positional (non-flag) argv elements.  When
#      combined with `multiple: true`, the positionals are collected into
#      an array.  This is the UNIX convention of "the rest of the args
#      go to one named field" expressed declaratively.  Compare yargs's
#      `_` field, commander's `.argument('<file...>')`, citty's
#      `type: "positional"`.
#
#   5. CHALK-TEMPLATE MARKUP IN description — descriptions use chalk-style
#      `{bold ...}`, `{underline ...}`, `{italic ...}` markup that
#      command-line-usage renders with ANSI colors:
#         description: 'A custom {bold handlebars} template {underline file}.'
#      This is the FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library with INLINE
#      RICH-TEXT MARKUP for help formatting.  Most others use plain text.
#
#   6. `typeLabel: '<file>'` FOR PLACEHOLDER RENDERING — separate from
#      `description`, `typeLabel` specifies the placeholder shown in
#      help output: `--template {underline file}` renders as
#      `--template file` (with file underlined).  Distinct from cleye's
#      bracket syntax, citty's `valueHint`.
#
#   7. SIBLING PACKAGES VIA command-line-usage AND command-line-commands —
#      to generate help text from the same OptionDefinition array, you
#      install `command-line-usage` and pass it sections + the same
#      defs.  For subcommands, install `command-line-commands` and
#      pass it a list of command names.  Each package is INDEPENDENTLY
#      VERSIONABLE.  This decomposition is rare among TS CLI libraries.
#
# THE command-line-args API SURFACE (verbatim from jsdoc2md cli-data.js)
#
#   import commandLineArgs from 'command-line-args';
#
#   const optionDefs = [
#       {
#           name: 'files',
#           alias: 'f',
#           type: String,
#           multiple: true,
#           defaultOption: true,
#           description: 'A list of jsdoc explain files...',
#           typeLabel: '{underline file} ...'
#       },
#       {
#           name: 'source',
#           type: String,
#           description: 'A string containing source code...'
#       },
#       {
#           name: 'help',
#           alias: 'h',
#           type: Boolean,
#           description: 'Print usage information'
#       },
#       {
#           name: 'heading-depth',
#           alias: 'd',
#           type: Number,
#           description: 'Root markdown heading depth.'
#       },
#       // ...
#   ];
#
#   const options = commandLineArgs(optionDefs);
#   // options.files       : string[]  (absorbs positionals)
#   // options.source      : string | undefined
#   // options.help        : boolean | undefined
#   // options.heading-depth : number | undefined
#
# OptionDefinition fields:
#   name           — long option name (also derived flag form: --name)
#   alias          — single-char short alias (-x)
#   type           — JS constructor (String / Number / Boolean) or custom fn
#   multiple       — boolean; if true, collects values into array
#   defaultValue   — value to use when option is omitted
#   defaultOption  — if true, captures non-flag positional args
#   group          — string for grouping in help output
#   description    — chalk-template markup help text
#   typeLabel      — placeholder string for help output
#
# Parsing options:
#   commandLineArgs(defs, { argv, partial, stopAtFirstUnknown, camelCase })
#     - argv: explicit argv slice
#     - partial: when true, unknown options collected into _unknown rather
#                than triggering errors (passthrough mode)
#     - stopAtFirstUnknown: stops parsing at first unknown arg
#     - camelCase: converts --foo-bar to opts.fooBar instead of opts['foo-bar']
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander.js               — fluent builder method chain (bundled)
#   * yargs                      — chainable builder (bundled)
#   * minimist                   — pure argv parser, no help/types
#   * vercel/arg                 — small typed parser
#   * meow                       — opinionated yargs wrapper
#   * mri                        — minimist successor by lukeed
#   * caporal                    — declarative + plugin
#   * nopt                       — npm's classic parser
#   * cmd-ts                     — type-safe TS builder
#   * clipanion (R480)           — class-based, Yarn Berry
#   * citty (R476)               — UnJS defineCommand
#   * cac                        — chainable typed
#   * sade                       — lukeed minimal
#   * type-flag                  — typed flag parser (cleye built on it)
#   * dthree/vorpal (R442)       — REPL-style interactive
#   * gluegun                    — full framework
#   * @stricli/core (R466)       — Bloomberg, zero-dep declarative
#   * cleye (R472)               — TypeScript-first (descended from CLA's
#                                  type-constructor idea ~7 years later)
#   * 75lb/command-line-args (THIS) — decomposed UNIX-philosophy parser
#                                  with chalk-template help markup
#
# command-line-args is the OLDEST entry on this list (first published 2014).
# Lloyd Brookes's UNIX-PHILOSOPHY DECOMPOSITION predates the modern
# TypeScript CLI design movement.  Many of the patterns later adopted by
# cleye (type-constructors), citty (object-array defs), stricli (data-driven
# parsing) trace their lineage to command-line-args's 2014 design.
#
# REAL-WORLD command-line-args USERS:
#
#   * jsdoc2md/jsdoc-to-markdown — JSDoc → Markdown (THIS, 1759*)
#   * 75lb/lws — Local Web Server
#   * 75lb/polyserve — Polymer dev server
#   * 75lb/dmd — Handlebars templates for jsdoc
#   * Hundreds of npm packages from the broader ecosystem; Lloyd's
#     command-line-* family is one of the most-downloaded CLI library
#     stacks on npm (~10M weekly combined downloads).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# JSDOC2MD'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from lib/cli-data.js)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   jsdoc2md [OPTIONS] <source-files>...
#   jsdoc2md --source '<javascript-source-code>'
#
# Input options:
#   -f, --files <files...>          Source files (or glob expressions) to
#                                   parse for JSDoc annotations (positional
#                                   default — bare args go here)
#   --source <code>                 Inline JavaScript source string
#   -c, --configure <file>          Path to a JSDoc configuration file
#                                   (passed to jsdoc -c)
#   --namepaths                     Print namepaths
#
# Template options:
#   -t, --template <file>           Custom handlebars template
#                                   (default: {{>main}})
#   --private                       Include @private identifiers
#   -d, --heading-depth <n>         Root heading depth (default 2 == ##)
#   --plugin <module...>            Installed packages with helper/partial
#                                   overrides
#   --helper <module...>            Handlebars helper module overrides
#   --partial <file...>             Handlebars partial file overrides
#   -l, --example-lang <lang>       Default @example block language
#                                   (e.g., js, ts, none, off)
#   --name-format                   Format identifier names as code
#                                   (wrap in backticks)
#   --no-gfm                        Disable GitHub-flavoured markdown
#   --separators                    Insert horizontal rules between members
#   --module-index-format <fmt>     Module index format
#                                   (none|grouped|table|dl)
#   --global-index-format <fmt>     Global index format
#   --param-list-format <fmt>       Parameter list format (list|table)
#   --property-list-format <fmt>    Property list format (list|table)
#   --member-index-format <fmt>     Member index format
#
# Output / inspection:
#   --json                          Print JSON template data (no rendering)
#   --jsdoc                         Print raw JSDoc data
#   --config                        Print all merged config and exit
#   --clear                         Clear the cache
#   --no-cache                      Disable caching for this invocation
#
# Help/version:
#   -h, --help                      Print usage information
#   --version                       Print version
#
# Configuration:
#   jsdoc2md merges options from (in priority order):
#     1. Command line
#     2. .jsdoc2md.json in current directory
#     3. package.json's "jsdoc2md" property
#     4. Defaults from cli-data.js
#
# =============================================================================

_jsdoc2md() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a example_langs index_formats list_formats

    example_langs=(
        'js:JavaScript'
        'ts:TypeScript'
        'jsx:JSX'
        'tsx:TSX'
        'hbs:Handlebars'
        'css:CSS'
        'json:JSON'
        'shell:Shell'
        'none:no language hint'
        'off:disable code blocks for @example'
    )

    index_formats=(
        'none:no index'
        'grouped:grouped index (default)'
        'table:table-formatted index'
        'dl:definition list'
    )

    list_formats=(
        'list:list format (default)'
        'table:table format'
    )

    _arguments -s \
        '*'{-f,--files}'[source files / glob expressions]:files:_files -g "*.(js|mjs|cjs|jsx|ts|tsx)"' \
        '--source[inline JavaScript source string]:source:' \
        '(-c --configure)'{-c,--configure}'[JSDoc configuration file]:config:_files' \
        '--namepaths[print namepaths]' \
        '(-t --template)'{-t,--template}'[custom handlebars template]:template:_files' \
        '--private[include @private identifiers]' \
        '(-d --heading-depth)'{-d,--heading-depth}'[root heading depth]:depth:' \
        '*--plugin[helper/partial override package]:plugin module:' \
        '*--helper[handlebars helper module override]:helper module:' \
        '*--partial[handlebars partial file override]:partial file:_files' \
        '(-l --example-lang)'{-l,--example-lang}'[default @example block language]:lang:->example_lang' \
        '--name-format[format identifier names as code (backticks)]' \
        '--no-gfm[disable GitHub-flavoured markdown]' \
        '--separators[insert horizontal rules between members]' \
        '--module-index-format[module index format]:format:->index_format' \
        '--global-index-format[global index format]:format:->index_format' \
        '--param-list-format[parameter list format]:format:->list_format' \
        '--property-list-format[property list format]:format:->list_format' \
        '--member-index-format[member index format]:format:->index_format' \
        '--json[print JSON template data, no rendering]' \
        '--jsdoc[print raw JSDoc data]' \
        '--config[print merged config and exit]' \
        '--clear[clear the cache]' \
        '--no-cache[disable caching for this invocation]' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print usage information]' \
        '--version[print version]' \
        '*:source file:_files -g "*.(js|mjs|cjs|jsx|ts|tsx)"' \
        && ret=0

    case $state in
        (example_lang)
            _describe -t example_langs '@example default language' example_langs && ret=0
            ;;
        (index_format)
            _describe -t index_formats 'index format' index_formats && ret=0
            ;;
        (list_format)
            _describe -t list_formats 'list format' list_formats && ret=0
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_jsdoc2md "$@"
